Here's how to implement all three requirements:

**1 & 2 — Intercept back navigation + confirmation dialog:**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` in your page's code-behind:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            // Fire-and-forget since the override is synchronous
            Dispatcher.Dispatch(async () =>
            {
                bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                    "Unsaved Changes",
                    "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
                    "Discard", "Stay");

                if (leave)
                    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
            });

            return true; // cancel the default navigation
        }

        return false; // no unsaved changes — allow normal back
    }
}
```

> **Note:** `OnBackButtonPressed` only fires for the **hardware/Android back button**. For the Shell toolbar back arrow, you need step 3.

**3 — Custom "Cancel" back button:**

Use `BackButtonBehavior` to replace the default arrow. In your XAML:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior
            TextOverride="Cancel"
            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

Then in your view model (or code-behind):

```csharp
public ICommand CancelCommand { get; }

public EditProductViewModel()
{
    CancelCommand = new Command(async () =>
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool leave = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!leave) return;
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    });
}
```

**Key points:**
- `BackButtonBehavior.Command` **replaces** the default navigation — Shell won't navigate automatically, so you must call `GoToAsync("..")` yourself.
- `TextOverride` shows "Cancel" in place of the arrow (on iOS it renders as text; on Android it replaces the icon).
- Both the toolbar button and the hardware back button are now covered.
